# Now we'll talk a little bit more about functions

# As a reminder, here are some examples:
  # print() - returns whatever you enter in the parentheses in your output
  # len() - returns the length of whatever data structure you pass through it
  # range(startNum, endNum, skipNum) - returns a range of numbers; you can convert it to a list to see the full list of numbers
# Some data structure conversion functions:
  # str() - converts whatever you pass through it to a string
  # int() - converts whatever you pass through it to an integer, typically do this with floats or numbered strings ('5')
  # list() - converts whatever you pass through it to a list, can use this on range()

# There are plenty more (especially in libraries) but we can also create our own functions.
# We want to create our own functions when we have repetitive chunks of code that can be reused.
# Let's look at how you would create a function:

def my_function(input):

  input += 1
  print(f'your input is now {input}')

  return input

# The function basically adds one to your input and prints the new value. The last line "return input" will return 
# the new value of input. You can assign this to a new variable. See the function in action below:

variable = my_function(1)

# "variable" will now be assigned to the value of 2 and "your input is now 2" will be printed

